Background

In class, we practiced webscraping with the Wikipedia page on the Men’s 100 metres world record progression. For this assignment, we’re going to continue with a similar theme, except we won’t only be limiting ourselves to world record times. The page that we’re scraping will also have a few complications that require extra (or at least different) steps.

Here is the webpage: All-time men’s best 100m.

Note: You are welcome to use the women’s all-time best 100m times if you prefer. However, please be aware that you may (will?) have to adjust some of the specific hints below. It will be become more obvious why once we get to the prediction section of the assignment.

Now is good time to load any packages that you will be needing, as well as set your preferred plotting theme, etc.

1) Read in the data

Take a look at the webpage in your browser. We only want the information contained in the main table at the top (i.e. ignore the rolling starts, manual timing, etc.) Read this table into R and call the resulting object m100_wp.

Hint: In class, we practiced identifying the correct HMTL elements with CSS selectors and SelectorGadget. However, you will almost certainly find it easier / more precise to scrape the table in this example via its XPath. Use your browser’s “Inspect” functionality to find and copy over this XPath. Remember to specify the “xpath” argument (instead of the default “css”) when pulling this information into R, i.e. rvest::html_element(xpath = "XPATH_HERE").

# Using read_html and html_text from rvest package
m100_wp <- read_html("http://www.alltime-athletics.com/m_100ok.htm",
                     xpath = "/html/body/center[3]/pre/text()[8]") %>% 
  
  html_nodes('pre')

# Some of the times were followed by an "A". So I'm removing these A's from all columns.
m100$time <- gsub("A", "", m100$time)

# Converting time from "character" to "numeric"
m100$time = as.numeric(m100$time)

m100$windspeed = as.numeric(m100$windspeed)

# as.numeric() turned "+-0.0" into NAs; so I'm converting them back to "0.0"
m100$windspeed[is.na(m100$windspeed)] <- 0

5) Subset to fastest times per year

  • It’s hard to fit a sensible model to the above data.
  • What might make more sense is to think of 100 metre times as following some kind of (approximately) deterministic process over the years.
  • Subset the data to the fastest time recorded in each year.
  • Call this new data frame m100_yr and then repeat the plot above, again highlighting Usain Bolt’s times.
m100_yr <- m100

# Retrieving only YYYY values rather than YYYY-MM-DD
m100_yr$date <- substr(m100$date, 1, 4) 

# Subsetting the data
m100_yr <- m100_yr %>%
           group_by(date) %>%
           filter( time == min(time) ) %>%
           arrange( desc(date), .by_group = TRUE )

usain_yr = m100_yr %>% filter(athlete == "Usain Bolt")

plot2 = ggplot(data = m100_yr, aes(x = date, y = time)) +
        geom_point(alpha = .5) + geom_point(data = usain_yr, aes(x = date, y = time), color = 'red') +
        labs(x = "Year", y = "Seconds", title = "Men's 100m Race Times") + theme_solarized() +
        theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, vjust = 0.5, hjust = 1))

plot2

6) Modeling and prediction

Imagine that you are back in the year 2005. You are tasked with fitting a model of year-best 100m times up until that point. Importantly, your model will also be used to predict the trajectory of future 100m times.

6.1) Fit a model

  • Start by fitting a simple regression model of your choice, using data that would have been available to you then (you can include 2005).
  • You are free to use whatever specification you prefer, but please be explicit by writing the model down. (Use dollar signs to demarcate LaTeX equations in R Markdown.)
  • Please also show me the actual regression results in a nicely-formatted table.

Hint: I’d advise excluding data from before 1975, since we don’t have consecutive or consistent records before then.

\[ Y = \beta_0 + \beta_1 X_1 + \epsilon \]

Our independent variable is the time of the race and our dependent variable is the date of the race. We would like to know the relationship between finish times and the date of the event to predict future times.

#change date and time to numeric
m100_yr$time = as.numeric(m100_yr$time)
m100_yr$date = as.numeric(m100_yr$date)


# Data up until 2005
# m100_yr_05 <- head(m100_yr, 38)
m100_yr_05 <- m100_yr %>% filter(date <= 2005 && date > 1975)

#change to date
# m100_yr_05$X9 = lubridate::dmy(m100_yr_05$X9)

# Simple Linear Model | running time (y) on date (x)
linear_model <- lm(time ~ date, m100_yr_05)

stargazer(linear_model, type = "text")

6.2) Prediction

Fast forward to the present day. Given your model and the available data in 2005, what year would you have predicted humanity reaching the current world record time of 9.58 seconds? How does this compare with the year that Usain Bolt actually set it (i.e. 2009). What do you make of this?

According to our model, we would reach a time of 9.58 seconds in the year 2033 (about 24 years off the actual year). This is obviously some years away from the year it was actually set (2009) but is also not a very bad prediction considering this is a very simple model with only one explanatory variable and a small sample size.

new_data <- m100_yr %>% filter(date > 2005)

new_date <- data.frame(
  date <- c(new_data$date)
)

# 1. Add predictions 
predicted <- predict(linear_model, new_date, interval = "confidence")
predicted

mydata2 <- cbind(date = new_data$date, time = new_data$time, predicted)
mydata2 <- as.data.frame(mydata2)

I want you to give me a sense of athletic achievement by country (including duplicate observations for the same athlete). Plot a world map, with a colour fill proportional to the number of fastest times that have been contributed by athletes of each country.

Hint: Use the sf-compatible “countries” data frame from the rnaturalearth package that I showed you in the spatial lecture. This will come with a column of “iso_a3” country codes that you can match (i.e. join) to the “country” column of the m100 data frame. There will likely be some mismatches because of inconsistencies in the ISO codes across these data frames. I won’t be too strict about this, though you may find the countrycode::countrycode() function a helpful alternative.

# Converted Country Codes into Country Names using countrycode and tibble

7.2. Interactive map

A major downside of the above static map is that some powerhouses of world athletics are geographically tiny nations in the Caribbean, which are very hard to see. One way to overcome this is to plot an interactive map using leaflet or one of the derivative packages that we discussed in the spatial lecture.

We are not sure why, but it seems the addMarkers() function is not rendering our data points correctly. The idea was to set a marker at each lat/long of our countries in the data frame below, with a popup of the number of best times above the marker. We got the markers to render just once, but for a reason we could not figure out the addMarkers() function is not rendering. We have attached an enlarged map of the Caribbean above to view the countries which may have been to small to view on the world map.

#dataframe with lat/long columns
leaflet_data = geocode(df,country="country")
#adding trinidad's lat/long (geocode didnt get it)
leaflet_data[26,][3] = 10.375722
leaflet_data[26,][4] = -61.233559

leaflet_data
#leaflet map
l <- leaflet(data = leaflet_data, width = 580, height = 500) %>%
  setView(lng = -443.800174, lat = 19.547561, zoom = 4.5) %>%
  addTiles() %>%
  addMarkers(lng = leaflet_data$long, lat = leaflet_data$lat,
             popup = as.character(leaflet_data$n),
             label = as.character(leaflet_data$n),
             data = leaflet_data)

l
